<h1>
Attorney General Ellison announces new Wage Theft Unit in AGO
</h1>
	<p class="lede">Will investigate and litigate complaints of wage theft and other workplace fraud and abuse perpetrated against Minnesotans of all backgrounds, especially the most vulnerable
</p>
	
	
	
	<p><strong>July 15,  2019 (SAINT PAUL) â </strong>On  the day that Governor Tim Walz ceremonially signed<strong> </strong>Minnesota&rsquo;s<strong> </strong>new  law to fight wage theft â the strongest law of its kind in the country â  Minnesota Attorney General Ellison announced that his office has formed a new  Wage Theft Unit dedicated to investigating and enforcing cases of wage theft.</p>
    <p>&ldquo;The  promise of America is that if you work hard and play by the rules, you&rsquo;ll get  ahead. But you can&rsquo;t get ahead if your boss is stealing your hard-earned  wages,&rdquo; Attorney General Ellison said. &ldquo;Wage theft is theft, pure and simple â  but even though we prosecute folks who steal from people, it&rsquo;s been hard to  hold bad employers accountable for stealing wages from their workers. </p>
    <p>&ldquo;Because  you should get every dollar you earned for every hour you worked, I&rsquo;ve started  a new Wage Theft Unit in the Attorney General&rsquo;s Office. Its sole purpose is to  use all of our powers to investigate wage theft and enforce the new law. It&rsquo;s  for Minnesotans from any job or industry and from any background or immigration  status â no exceptions â who are having their wages stolen or are experiencing  other kinds fraud or abuse. It&rsquo;s also for any employer who is playing by the  rules but is being hurt by having to compete against a business that is  stealing wages and breaking the law,&rdquo; Ellison continued.</p>
    <p>Wage theft  can take many forms: having hours shaved off your paycheck; being forced to  work off the clock; not getting paid for overtime; being paid at a lower rate  than promised, sometimes even below minimum wage; being paid in cash or other  forms like gift cards, with no Social Security, unemployment, or worker&rsquo;s comp  withheld; being misclassified as an independent contractor; and more. </p>
    <p>The  Minnesota Attorney General&rsquo;s Office Wage Theft Unit will protect and advance  the economic rights of all Minnesota residents, especially those from  communities and backgrounds that are most vulnerable to theft and abuse, who  have traditionally lacked access to the courts and attorneys.&nbsp;The Unit  will investigate and litigate cases involving patterns and practices affecting  economic rights and other persistent issues that cause Minnesotan workers not  to receive the wages they are entitled to.&nbsp;The Unit will also monitor  emerging labor and employment issues and dialogue with other government  entities, community groups, and the business community to increase awareness of  economic rights issues and to identify bad actors violating those rights. </p>
    <p>Staffing  the Wage Theft Unit are Jonathan Moler and Ana Vergara. </p>
    <p><strong>Jonathan  Moler</strong> is an  Assistant Attorney General whose practice focuses on economic- and  social-justice work.&nbsp; In the Attorney General&rsquo;s Office, he has previously  represented the Department of Labor and Industry and the Department of Human  Rights in their work to make workplaces fairer, safer, and free from  discrimination. Prior to joining the Attorney General&rsquo;s Office, Jonathan  advocated for workers&rsquo; rights as an attorney at Nichols Kaster, PLLP. As part  of the Office&rsquo;s Wage Theft Unit, Jonathan will develop and litigate cases to  protect Minnesotan workers&rsquo; economic rights and will work to strengthen the  Office&rsquo;s bonds with governmental and community partners who share those  goals.&nbsp; </p>
    <p><strong>Ana Vergara</strong> joins the Minnesota Attorney  General&rsquo;s Office as a Wage Theft Investigator.&nbsp;Most recently, Ana worked  at the Amnesty International headquarters in Washington, D.C. as a refugee  campaigner: her campaign work focused on asylum seekers at the southern border  and family separation. The Humphrey School of Public Affairs, where she earned  a master&rsquo;s degree, awarded Ana the 2019 Paul and Sheila Wellstone Award for  Public Action for embodying the spirit, passion, and dedication of the late  U.S. senator and his wife. Ana will continue her public service as the  Congressional District 2 representative for the Minnesota Council of Latino  Affairs.&nbsp; </p>
    <p>Any  Minnesotan who has had wages stolen by an employer or is experiencing other  kinds of fraud or abuse in the workplace should contact the Minnesota Attorney  General&rsquo;s Office at (651) 296-3353 (metro) or  (800) 657-3787 (Greater Minnesota) or write the Office at:</p>
    <p class="center"><strong>Office of Minnesota Attorney General  Keith Ellison</strong><br>
      445 Minnesota Street, Suite 600<br>
      St. Paul, MN 55101.</p>
